-- ── CoCalc (cocalc.com) ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$CoCalc (cocalc.com) is a cloud-based collaborative platform for computational mathematics, data science, and scientific computing, built around Jupyter notebooks, SageMath, Python, R, and LaTeX. Operated by SageMath, Inc. since 2015, it combines real-time multi-user editing with course management tools used by university instructors to run programming and math classes.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium: free tier plus paid license upgrades for internet access, more compute and storage, and course licenses, priced by resources and number of projects or students$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free tier available; paid license upgrades scale with compute, storage, and number of projects$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2015, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Small team, reported at roughly five people, operated by SageMath, Inc.$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Renton, Washington, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$CoCalc Review: Cloud Jupyter, SageMath and LaTeX Platform$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$CoCalc is a collaborative cloud platform for Jupyter, SageMath, Python, R and LaTeX. See 2026 pricing, features, pros, cons and use cases.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$CoCalc, found at cocalc.com, is a cloud-based collaborative computing platform originally launched in 2015 by William Stein, the mathematician who also created the SageMath computer algebra system, under the company SageMath, Inc. CoCalc began life as SageMathCloud, focused on running Sage worksheets in the browser, and has since expanded into a general-purpose environment for computational mathematics, data science, and scientific computing. The platform's core offering is real-time collaborative editing of Jupyter notebooks, SageMath worksheets, Python and R scripts, and LaTeX documents, all running inside cloud-hosted Linux projects that multiple users can view and edit simultaneously, similar to how a shared document editor allows several people to edit the same text file at once. Each CoCalc project is effectively a private Linux computing environment with a persistent file system, terminal access, and pre-installed scientific software stacks, so users do not need to install SageMath, Jupyter kernels, or a LaTeX distribution locally. Beyond individual use, CoCalc is widely used by university instructors for teaching programming, mathematics, statistics, and data science courses. Its course management features let an instructor create a course project, automatically generate individual student projects, distribute and collect assignments, and grade Jupyter notebooks or other files without students needing to install anything beyond a web browser. This teaching-oriented workflow, combined with LaTeX support for typesetting problem sets and papers, differentiates CoCalc from more general-purpose notebook hosting services. CoCalc's pricing follows a freemium model. Free accounts can create and run projects, but without internet access from within the project and with limited compute and storage resources. Paid license upgrades, purchased as subscriptions or one-time licenses, unlock outbound internet access, more member-hosted, higher-priority compute, additional memory and disk, and the ability to run projects continuously. Pricing scales with the number of concurrent projects or students and the amount of compute, memory, and disk requested, and CoCalc publishes an academic discount, reported at around 40 percent, for educators, students, and hobbyists, alongside separate business pricing for commercial use. Course licenses let an instructor cover an entire class under a single license rather than requiring each student to pay individually. The company behind CoCalc, SageMath, Inc., is a small, bootstrapped business headquartered in the Seattle area, specifically Renton, Washington, reported to run with a team of roughly five people and to have grown to around 550,000 dollars in annual revenue without external venture funding, according to third-party revenue-tracking sources. The platform's underlying software is developed in large part in the open, with a public GitHub repository under sagemathinc/cocalc, reflecting its roots in the open-source SageMath project. CoCalc's primary competitors and comparison points include Google Colab, other Jupyter-based hosting services, Overleaf for LaTeX-only workflows, and general cloud IDE or notebook platforms, but its distinguishing combination is native, tightly integrated support for SageMath alongside Jupyter and LaTeX, plus built-in course and classroom management, all inside a single collaborative cloud workspace. It is most commonly recommended for university-level math, statistics, and computer science instruction, individual researchers who want zero-setup access to SageMath and Jupyter, and small teams collaborating on numerical or symbolic computing work.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '8538d67b-ef8f-47c5-95ac-808d9107a1d3';

